    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-27T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-27T13:00:00-05:00" n="865"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d865">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">300.115(39)/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-27T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 27, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 27—3:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2192. Your 1203. We have asked Ministry of Economic War[fare] for information
                    requested your cable. In informal discussion they have stated that they would
                    endeavor to furnish us with statement showing dates of arrival at place of
                    detention and dates of requisition, release, reference to Prize Courts or other
                    disposition in regard to American war [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>] vessels, that
                    this would entail considerable work and that they could promise no date when
                    such information could be compiled. With regard to American cargoes they did not
                    believe this would be humanly possible as there had been several hundred ships
                    detained and it was in many cases difficult to tell whether the cargo consisting
                    of many items was American owned or not, legal proceedings in Prize Court at
                    times being necessary to determine that fact. See our cable No. 2030<note n="78"
                        xml:id="d865fn78">Not printed.</note> and No. 2098.<note n="79"
                        xml:id="d865fn79">October 19, 6 p.m., <ref target="#pg_795">p.
                        795</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
